\par <#/>}{\fs24\lang2057 The other evening I sat at home leisurely watching the talking box. <#/>It was a hot and humid evening when the children's show depicting cartoons ice skating was very refreshing.
\par <#/>I have developed some interest in the children's programmes because they remind me of the good old days.
\par <#/>And I am sure they are also of interest to other adults too, at least to those who care about the welfare and future of the adults of tomorrow.
\par <#/>I could notice broad smiles and <-/laughters> from my children. <#/>In brief, they were happy and joyful.
\par <#/>They have always expressed the wish to join me around the TV set whenever the 45-minute children's programme is over. <#/>But I have always refused to succumb to the
ir wish to have a look at programmes meant for adults. <#/>You never know what will be on stage.
\par <#/>I am very much ware that there are those who call themselves liberated by urban civilisation and feel this is a wrong attitude and an exhibition of selfishness and unfairness.
\par <#/>But I am one of those "uncivilised" who feel that this rule of not allowing children to see programmes meant for adults has all the ingredients of perfection in a society which strives for a sense of morality.
\par <#/>Once the cartoon series were over, came a local show in which pupils were competing to solve riddles, some of which were new to me because they touched on latest inventions, developments and technology. <#/>It was very interesting.
\par <#/>After the riddles were put on the floor and solved, there appeared in a three-minute script of a carnival in Brazil, a merry making festival of colour and fun.
\par <#/>It was a colourful extravaganza in which the old and the young participated in different styles. <#/>They were celebrating the New Year.
\par <#/>When the 10-minute masterpiece of fanfare came to an end and the TVZ brought back the viewers from Rio de Janeiro, one of my daughters - like a lost kid at the end of a hard day's play - turned to me and asked a simple, but tormenting question:
 "Daddy, why don't we have such a thing in Zanzibar"?
\par <#/>I kept quiet for a while and after a deep thought I felt it was unfair if I did not respond. <#/>I knew that the question was simple, but it was not that simple to give an honest answer.
\par <#/>This was because the matter touched the roots of Zanzibar, currently shaken up by latest inventions and adoption of imported cultures brought in by travellers, cinemas, television and videos.
\par <#/>The question touched on the current trend of the Isles' lost images, but I had to tell her and as well as to bring to the attention of those who care the images which make Zanzibar what it is are dwindling.
\par <#/>In fact Zanzibar had until in the recent past had a similar carnival to the one of Brazil. <#/>But while the Lat
in American festival has survived and continues to be the pride of the Latin Americans, the Zanzibar one has been neglected and dumped in the files of history.
\par <#/>Unfortunately, nobody seems to care! Instead, the Islanders seem to be in a hurry to shed their cultural heritage and pick up trends of the so-called modern era. <#/>Customs and way of life of their predecessors are considered to be outdated.
\par <#/>While the Brazilian carnival is marked to celebrate the New Year, the Zanzibar festival is dedicated to welcome the Holy Month of Ramadhan.
\par <#/>I still remember the good old days when I was young. <#/>Participants would be busy for weeks preparing for the show on the wheels of the <ea/>}{\i\fs24\lang2057 hamali}{\fs24\lang2057  carts.
\par <#/>Its mass participation, with spectators jamming the streets made it unique.
\par <#/>This used to be a night when the whole of the Zanzibar town was transformed into an explosion of colour and sound. <#/>People danced, jumped and sang the whole night.
\par <#/>The other sad, but somehow funny part of it, was that at the end of the carnival, fighting among some competitors or their supporters was a common phenomenon. <#/>Fists and sticks were considered to be part and parcel of the festival.
\par <#/>However, certain rules had to be observed during the fighting, such as that one must confront an opponent of his age and should only use hands and sticks.
\par <#/>And when an opponent raised his hands or utters words of surrender the fighting must stop forthwith.
\par <#/>Then a hand shake must follow, perhaps with vows for vengeance at the next show the following year.
\par <#/>At one stage, the British colonialists had strong reservations against the carnival. <#/>They felt it was associated with some sort of an arranged forum to settle old scores. <#/>To their minds it was also connected wi
th witchcraft, evil spirits and other hidden intentions.
\par <#/>But public pressure from the local population forced them to accept it as integral part of the Zanzibar culture. <#/>It touched thesensitive parts of the Isles }{\b\v\fs24\lang2057 <&/>grammar}{\fs24\lang2057  social fabric.
\par <#/>Perhaps what convinced them to succumb was the fact that the festival, which used to be held during the Muslim month of Shaaban, was part of the celebrations to welcome the holy month of Ramadhan.
\par <#/>During the show, some characters, would appear with funny faces, depicting various animals, birds sea creatures and unknown characters, such as those of devils and <ea/>}{\i\fs24\lang2057 
jinnis. <#/>These clever disguises created a lot of interest among the young ones }{\b\v\fs24\lang2057 <&/>orth}{\fs24\lang2057 .
\par <#/>I still remember when I was about 12 years. <#/>I had gone to see the festival with my uncle who had to keep on patting me again and again so as to stay awake as we stood besides the street waiting for the carnival procession.
\par <#/>And when the <ea/>}{\i\fs24\lang2057 hamali}{\fs24\lang2057  carts approached, my sleep just faded.
\par <#/>On board of one of the carts, decorated with colourful papers, paintings and flowers were crows crying madly.
\par <#/>There was an old man busy selling fruits while another one }{\b\v\fs24\lang2057 <+_was>}{\v\fs24\lang2057  }{\fs24\lang2057 fishing with a rope made up of coconut fibre. <#/>From that time till today I keep
 on wondering how they trained those crows to feel in their natural habitat.
\par <#/>On board another cart was a well clad school teacher, busy writing with charcoal on a white board. <#/>It was a biology lesson. <#/>I remember vividly when he asked the studen
ts, some as young as four and some as old as 50, which was thicker... blood or water.
\par <#/>The old man replied emphatically:
\par <#/>"Blood". <#/>But soon after, one of }{\b\v\fs24\lang2057 <+_article>}{\fs24\lang2057  young kids shouted: "No... No... <#/>It is porridge". <#/>The teacher laughed, b
ut the students showed angry faces and one of them wanted to beat the little kid for lack of seriousness in the class. <#/>What a contrast!
\par <#/>Another incident which is still fresh in my mind involves a short, muscular, strong featured labourer with <-/acquiline> nose and deep set eyes. <#/>His <-/nick name> was Morombe.
\par <#/>He had carried mangoes in a wheel barrow and complained that he had worked so hard at a building site and was now selling the fruits and yet he could not make ends meet.
\par <#/>A friend asked him what was wrong with him and Morombe said he had a football team of 13 - eleven players and two substitutes.
\par <#/>He was a very good actor and really won the hearts of the audience, but I still doubt <-/todate> if the laughing audience understood the serious message behind that comedy at that time, now more than 30 years ago.
